## Feature 1: Grid Overlay

Add a visible SVG grid behind all plan objects.

Default settings:

```ts
grid: {
  enabled: true;
  minorSpacingMm: 100;
  majorSpacingMm: 1000;
  showMinor: true;
  showMajor: true;
}
```

Requirements:

* grid renders behind objects
* grid pans with the canvas
* grid scales with zoom
* grid aligns to world coordinates in millimetres
* grid can be toggled on/off
* minor spacing can be selected from:

  * 50 mm
  * 100 mm
  * 250 mm
  * 500 mm
  * 1000 mm
* major spacing should remain a multiple of minor spacing
* settings persist in LocalStorage and JSON export/import
* grid is not included in SVG export by default

Implementation preference:

* Use SVG patterns if practical.
* Avoid rendering thousands of individual grid lines.

Acceptance criteria:

* Grid is visible on load.
* Grid stays aligned while panning.
* Grid scales correctly while zooming.
* Grid can be hidden and shown.
* Grid spacing changes correctly.
* Grid settings survive reload.

## Feature 2: Snap-to-Grid

Add snapping for floor-plan editing.

Default settings:

```ts
snap: {
  enabled: true;
  spacingMm: 100;
}
```

Requirements:

Snapping applies to:

* object creation
* object dragging
* object resizing
* dimension-line endpoints
* wall start/end points
* door/window placement along walls where applicable

Modifier behavior:

* Alt/Option temporarily disables snapping.
* Shift is reserved for angle constraint in wall drawing.

Add helpers:

```ts
snapValue(value: number, spacing: number): number

snapPoint(
  point: { x: number; y: number },
  spacing: number
): { x: number; y: number }
```

Acceptance criteria:

* Moving objects snaps to the active spacing.
* Resizing objects snaps dimensions/handles.
* New objects are placed on snapped coordinates.
* Holding Alt/Option bypasses snapping.
* Snap setting survives reload.

## Feature 3: Selected-Object Dimension Labels

Show dimensions on the canvas when an object is selected.

Requirements:

* show width and depth
* show rotation if non-zero
* update live during drag/resize
* remain readable at different zoom levels
* not block pointer interaction
* hidden when nothing is selected
* not exported by default

Example labels:

```text
1200 x 600 mm
Rot 45 deg
```

Implementation preference:

* Use SVG text if simple.
* Use pointer-events="none" for overlays.
* Keep text size readable regardless of zoom.

Acceptance criteria:

* Selecting an object shows dimensions.
* Resizing updates dimensions immediately.
* Moving object keeps labels attached.
* Rotated objects still show labels.
* Labels do not interfere with selection or dragging.

## Feature 4: Dimension-Line Tool

Add a persistent dimension annotation tool.

User flow:

1. User selects Dimension tool.
2. User clicks first point.
3. User moves mouse and sees preview.
4. User clicks second point.
5. Dimension annotation is created.
6. Annotation displays measured distance.

Preferred data model:

```ts
type DimensionAnnotation = {
  id: string;
  type: 'dimension';
  name?: string;
  start: { x: number; y: number };
  end: { x: number; y: number };
  offsetMm?: number;
  layerId?: string;
  locked?: boolean;
  visible?: boolean;
  memo?: string;
};
```

If a separate annotation collection is too disruptive, extend the existing drawable object model safely.

Requirements:

* supports horizontal, vertical, and diagonal measurements
* start/end stored in millimetres
* distance label centered on line
* tick marks or arrowheads at endpoints
* label background for readability
* selectable
* deletable
* movable if practical
* included in undo/redo
* persists in LocalStorage
* included in JSON export/import
* included in SVG export

Distance formatting:

* under 1000 mm: `850 mm`
* 1000 mm and above: `1.20 m`

Acceptance criteria:

* Dimension tool creates a dimension line.
* Preview appears before second click.
* Displayed distance is correct.
* Dimension can be selected and deleted.
* Dimension survives reload.
* Dimension exports to JSON and SVG.
* Undo/redo works.

## Feature 5: Improved Wall Drawing

Improve the wall tool so walls are drawn as floor-plan wall segments.

Current legacy wall shapes must continue to render.

New wall data model:

```ts
type WallObject = {
  id: string;
  type: 'wall';
  name: string;
  start: { x: number; y: number };
  end: { x: number; y: number };
  thicknessMm: number;
  heightMm?: number;
  layerId?: string;
  locked?: boolean;
  visible?: boolean;
  stroke?: string;
  fill?: string;
  memo?: string;
};
```

Default wall thickness:

```text
100 mm
```

User flow:

1. User selects Wall tool.
2. User clicks start point.
3. User moves mouse and sees wall preview.
4. User clicks endpoint.
5. Wall is created.
6. Endpoint becomes start point for next wall segment.
7. Esc exits wall drawing.

Requirements:

* wall has start and end points
* wall thickness editable
* wall length shown while drawing
* endpoints snap to grid
* endpoints snap to nearby wall endpoints if practical
* Shift constrains angle to 45-degree increments
* Alt/Option disables snapping
* selected wall shows endpoint handles
* endpoints can be dragged
* entire wall can be moved
* wall length, thickness, start/end, and angle shown in properties panel
* legacy wall objects continue to work
* JSON import/export remains compatible
* SVG export includes new walls

Acceptance criteria:

* Click-to-draw wall works.
* Continuous wall drawing works.
* Esc exits wall mode.
* Shift angle constraint works.
* Length preview appears.
* Wall thickness can be edited.
* Wall endpoints can be edited.
* Existing saved wall shapes still render.
* Undo/redo works.
* JSON and SVG export work.

## Feature 6: Doors and Windows Attached to Walls

Add semantic door and window objects attached to wall segments.

Data model:

```ts
type DoorObject = {
  id: string;
  type: 'door';
  name: string;
  wallId: string;
  offsetMm: number;
  widthMm: number;
  swingDirection: 'left' | 'right';
  swingAngleDeg: number;
  layerId?: string;
  locked?: boolean;
  visible?: boolean;
  memo?: string;
};

type WindowObject = {
  id: string;
  type: 'window';
  name: string;
  wallId: string;
  offsetMm: number;
  widthMm: number;
  layerId?: string;
  locked?: boolean;
  visible?: boolean;
  memo?: string;
};
```

Defaults:

```text
door width: 900 mm
door swing angle: 90 deg
door swing direction: left
window width: 1200 mm
```

User flow:

1. User selects Door or Window tool.
2. User hovers over a wall.
3. Placement preview appears on nearest wall point.
4. User clicks to place.
5. Door/window attaches to wall.
6. User can drag it along the wall.
7. User can edit width and relevant properties.

Placement rules:

* calculate closest point on wall
* clamp offset so object stays within wall length
* store position as offset from wall start
* derive rendered position from parent wall geometry
* align symbol to wall angle

Door rendering:

* draw door leaf
* draw swing arc
* align to wall
* visual overlay is acceptable
* do not implement boolean wall cutouts unless simple

Window rendering:

* draw clear window symbol centered on wall
* align to wall
* visually distinguish from wall

Requirements:

* selectable
* deletable
* draggable along parent wall
* layer/visibility/lock behavior consistent with other objects
* width editable
* door swing direction editable
* door swing angle editable
* persists in LocalStorage
* included in JSON import/export
* included in SVG export
* undo/redo works

Acceptance criteria:

* Door can be placed on a wall.
* Window can be placed on a wall.
* Door/window follows wall angle.
* Door/window can be dragged along the wall.
* Width can be edited.
* Door swing direction can be changed.
* Door/window survives reload.
* Door/window exports to JSON and SVG.
* Undo/redo works.

